\section*{Pascal's Identity}

Pascal's identity, first derived by Blaise Pascal in $19^{\text {th }}$ century, states that the number of ways to choose $k$ elements from $n$ elements is equal to the summation of number of ways to choose ( $k-1$ ) elements from ( $\mathrm{n}-1$ ) elements and the number of ways to choose elements from $\mathrm{n}-1$ elements.

Mathematically, for any positive integers k and n : ${ }_{n} C_{k}={ }_{n-1} C_{k-1+n-1} C_{k}$
Proof -
$$\begin{aligned}
& \\
& =(n-1)!(k-1)!(n-k)!+(n-1)!k!(n-k-1)! \\
& =(n-1)!(k k!(n-k)!+n-k k!(n-k)!) \\
& =(n-1)!n k!(n-k)! \\
& =n!k!(n-k)! \\
& =n C k
\end{aligned}$$

