\section*{Introduction to probability}

Probability is the science of studying the outcomes of random phenomena.
A phenomenon is called random if individual outcomes are uncertain but the long-term pattern of many outcomes is predictable.

To determine the probability of a specific outcome of a probability experiment (random phenomenon) the experiment is repeated a large number of times and we look at the ratio of times that the outcome occurred.
- Example: The outcome of the experiment of tossing a coin is a random phenomenon. The probability that the outcome is "Heads" can be found by tossing the coin a large number of times.

\section*{Probability Models}

A probability model is a mathematical representation of a random phenomenon. It is defined by its sample space, events within the sample space, and probabilities associated with each event. The sample space $S$ for a probability model is the set of all possible outcomes.

\section*{Terminology:}

For any probability experiment (or a random phenomenon)
$\checkmark$ The collection of all the possible outcomes of the experiment is called the Sample Space.
$\checkmark$ An event is any sub-collection of outcomes in the sample space.
$\checkmark$ A simple event is any single outcome.
$\checkmark$ The complement of an event $A$, denoted $\bar{A}$, is the set of all outcomes not in $A$.
$\checkmark$ A probability model (or a probability distribution) is a process of assigning to the outcomes and events in a sample space a value that represents the probability for that outcome to occur. If $x$ is an outcome, the probability of $x$ will be denoted by $P(x)$. If $E$ is an event, the probability of $E$ will be denoted by $P(E)$.
$\checkmark$ The assignment in a probability model must satisfy the following rules:
- For any event or outcome, the probability is a number between 0 and 1.
- The probability of the sample space is 1.
- If two events A and B do are disjoint, i.e. have no outcome in common, then the probability $\mathbf{P}(\mathbf{A}$ or $\mathbf{B})$ that one or the other occurs is the $\operatorname{sum} \boldsymbol{P}(\boldsymbol{A})+\boldsymbol{P}(\boldsymbol{B})$ of the individual probabilities of the events.
- The probability of an impossible (empty) event is 0 .

For a finite (discrete) probability space, these rules guarantee that the probabilities of the individual events must add up to 1 .

